"""**Part 3: Implementation of Logistic Regression From
Scratch (30 Marks)**

You are required to implement **Binary Logistic Regression Model** from scratch keeping in view all the discussions from the class lectures.</br>

*   Sigmoid Function </br>

The sigmoid function is used on the classifier to compute the probability of the feature vector x belonging to that class. Then the label of the classifier which returns the highest probability is assigned to x. </br>
**If Scikit-Learn is used in this part, you will NOT get any credit.** </br>
It is HIGHLY recommended that you use matrix multiplication in your implementation instead of for loops to avoid unnecessary runtime. 
![Sigmoid.png](data:image/png;base64,)
"""

# Implement sigmoid function here
# Code Here
def sigmoid(x):
  return 1/(1+np.exp(-x))

# ---------

"""

*   Cross Entropy Loss </br>

![Loss.png](data:image/png;base64,)

"""

# Implement Cross Entropy Loss here
# Code Here
def loss_func(X,y,y_pred,theta):
  samples = X.shape[0]
  return (-1)* (np.dot(y.T,np.log(y_pred))\
   + np.dot((1-y).T, np.log(1 - y_pred )))

# ---------

"""* Batch Gradient Descent </br>

We require you to incorporate **L2 regularization** in the loss function, that is:  </br>
![Descent.png](data:image/png;base64,)

where L(θ) is cross-entropy loss and λ is the regularization parameter. </br>

You will compute the derivative of the new loss expression and update the weights of the model using the derivative during the implementation of batch gradient descent.  </br>

Run your batch gradient descent function for large number of epochs, e.g. around 1000, to get good F1-scores.
"""

# Implement Batch Gradient Descent here
# Code Here
def gradient_descent(X,Y,lr,lambda_):
  samples = X.shape[0]
  loss = []
  theta = np.zeros(X.shape[1]) #Initial weights --equal to the number of features
  b = 0
  for i in range(1000):
    h = np.dot(X,theta) + b     
    y_pred  = sigmoid(h)  
    loss.append(loss_func(X,Y,y_pred,theta))

    d_theta = (2/samples) * np.dot(X.T, (y_pred-Y)) + (lambda_/samples) * theta
    db = (2/samples) * np.sum(y_pred-Y)
    theta-= lr*d_theta
    b-= lr*db
  return theta,b,loss
# ---------

"""

*   Prediction Function </br>

It predicts the labels of test data.

"""

# Implement Prediction Function here
# Code Here
def pred(X,theta,b):
  h = np.dot(X,theta) + b     
  y_pred  = sigmoid(h)
  return [1 if i>0.5 else 0 for i in y_pred]  
# ---------

"""Implementation: </br>
Using the above functions, implement your Logistic Regression Classifier. </br>
Remember to store the training loss for result visualization. </br>

"""

# Implement Logistic Regression 
